<h2>Population</h2>

<p>
  Population is your workforce. Buildings need workers; without enough people,
  some buildings will not produce anything when you end a turn.
</p>

<h4>Population Cap</h4>
<p>
  Your maximum population is determined by <strong>Houses</strong> and <strong>Town Centers</strong>.
  Each House provides <%= @buildings['house']&.people&.to_i || 100 %> population cap.
  Each Town Center provides <%= @buildings['town_center']&.people&.to_i || 100 %> population cap.
  The minimum population is always 100 (you can never go below this).
</p>

<h4>Population Growth</h4>
<p>
  Population growth is controlled by your <strong>Food Ratio</strong> setting (set on the Management screen).
  Higher ratios consume more food but grow your population faster.
</p>
<table class="table table-bordered table-sm">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th class="text-center">Food Ratio</th>
      <th class="text-center">Population Change / Turn</th>
      <th class="text-center">Food Multiplier</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td class="text-center">Very Low (−2)</td><td class="text-center">−200 to −100</td><td class="text-center">0.45×</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="text-center">Low (−1)</td><td class="text-center">−100 to −50</td><td class="text-center">0.75×</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="text-center">Normal (0)</td><td class="text-center">−30 to +50</td><td class="text-center">1×</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="text-center">High (+1)</td><td class="text-center">+50 to +100</td><td class="text-center">1.5×</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="text-center">Very High (+2)</td><td class="text-center">+100 to +200</td><td class="text-center">2.5×</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="text-center">Maximum (+3)</td><td class="text-center">+200 to +400</td><td class="text-center">4×</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="text-center">Extreme (+4)</td><td class="text-center">+400 to +800</td><td class="text-center">8×</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p class="text-secondary"><small>Growth is divided by 10,000 so actual net change per turn depends on your total population.</small></p>

<h4>Food Consumption</h4>
<p>
  Population eats food every turn based on the food ratio and game settings.
  Your civilization may modify how many people one unit of food feeds.
  If your food supply runs out:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7% of your population starves</strong> each turn food is negative.</li>
  <li>Soldiers on campaigns survive at a 95% rate when food runs out.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Winter Heating</h4>
<p>
  During winter months (November–February, turns 11–2), people consume wood for heating.
  Default: 1 wood heats approximately <strong>100–125 people</strong> (depends on game settings).
  If there is not enough wood for heating, some people will <strong>freeze</strong>:
  the number of people without heat divided by 8 will die each winter turn.
</p>

<h4>Working Population</h4>
<p>
  At most <strong>50%</strong> of your population can work as construction builders.
  The remaining population fills jobs in production buildings.
  If you have more jobs than workers, some buildings will be idle — watch the status
  panel in the Builders tab for a warning.
</p>

<h4>Civilization Modifiers</h4>
<p>Some civilizations change population mechanics:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Franks</strong> — slower population growth (0.80× modifier)</li>
  <li><strong>Mongols</strong> — faster growth (1.4×), people eat less food</li>
  <li><strong>Chinese</strong> — fastest growth (2.0×)</li>
  <li><strong>Byzantines</strong> — people eat less food (1 food per 60 people)</li>
  <li><strong>Vikings</strong> — 1 wood heats 125 people (more efficient heating)</li>
</ul>
